1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,966
So a couple of years ago,

2
00:00:00,966 --> 00:00:01,980
a friend told me about a novel idea that he had,

3
00:00:02,946 --> 00:00:04,990
it was this big, grand vision, that would take him

4
00:00:04,990 --> 00:00:07,340
a really long time to write and he knew it

5
00:00:07,339 --> 00:00:09,960
and in his defense, he did start working in earnest on it

6
00:00:09,961 --> 00:00:12,638
for the first few days after having that idea,

7
00:00:12,637 --> 00:00:15,253
but as you could probably guess, after those first few days,

8
00:00:15,253 --> 00:00:18,233
his motivation waned and he stopped working on the book.

9
00:00:18,234 --> 00:00:19,124
Now when this happened,

10
00:00:19,123 --> 00:00:20,627
we didn't wanna see him give up on the project,

11
00:00:20,629 --> 00:00:22,209
but one of the suggestions we gave him

12
00:00:22,208 --> 00:00:24,530
was to first cut his teeth on some smaller projects,

13
00:00:24,530 --> 00:00:27,164
maybe work on some short stories or some blog posts,

14
00:00:27,166 --> 00:00:28,540
just something to basically get him

15
00:00:28,539 --> 00:00:30,501
into the habit of writing regularly,

16
00:00:30,501 --> 00:00:32,066
but his response to these suggestions

17
00:00:32,067 --> 00:00:33,942
was that he didn't wanna waste his time

18
00:00:33,942 --> 00:00:36,154
on these smaller projects, if he was gonna write,

19
00:00:36,155 --> 00:00:38,175
he only wanted to tackle his grand vision

20
00:00:38,174 --> 00:00:39,742
and this happens to a lot of people,

21
00:00:39,743 --> 00:00:40,742
when they set big goals,

22
00:00:40,741 --> 00:00:43,647
they don't wanna detour from their grand vision

23
00:00:43,648 --> 00:00:45,239
to work on something a bit smaller

24
00:00:45,238 --> 00:00:46,794
and this mindset, as well-intentioned

25
00:00:46,795 --> 00:00:48,532
and determined as it may seem

26
00:00:48,533 --> 00:00:49,998
is one of the biggest reasons

27
00:00:49,999 --> 00:00:53,118
why people fail to achieve their big goals.

28
00:00:53,118 --> 00:00:54,557
Far from being a waste of time,

29
00:00:54,557 --> 00:00:56,540
these detours from your grand vision

30
00:00:56,539 --> 00:00:58,309
which I like to call intermediate goals

31
00:00:58,310 --> 00:01:00,502
are actually essential for helping you build

32
00:01:00,503 --> 00:01:02,428
the skillset you need to actually

33
00:01:02,427 --> 00:01:04,118
execute on that bigger project,

34
00:01:04,118 --> 00:01:06,256
essentially no matter what the goal is, that you've set,

35
00:01:06,257 --> 00:01:07,648
you need to be able to see regular

36
00:01:07,649 --> 00:01:09,705
and tangible progress being made,

37
00:01:09,704 --> 00:01:11,517
otherwise your motivation is going to wane

38
00:01:11,518 --> 00:01:12,953
and you're gonna stop working on it

39
00:01:12,953 --> 00:01:13,786
and to illustrate this point,

40
00:01:13,786 --> 00:01:15,131
I wanna share a couple of examples with you

41
00:01:15,131 --> 00:01:16,891
and we're gonna start with Neal Stephenson,

42
00:01:16,891 --> 00:01:19,298
who is one of my favorite authors in the world.

43
00:01:19,299 --> 00:01:20,468
Stephenson is one of those authors,

44
00:01:20,468 --> 00:01:22,879
that writes huge, dauntingly complex novels

45
00:01:22,881 --> 00:01:24,892
typically in the hard science fiction genre

46
00:01:24,891 --> 00:01:26,203
and one of his books, Snow Crash,

47
00:01:26,204 --> 00:01:27,820
which is one of my personal favorites

48
00:01:27,820 --> 00:01:29,582
actually coined the term, avatar,

49
00:01:29,584 --> 00:01:30,916
at least in its context of the term

50
00:01:30,915 --> 00:01:33,684
related to computers and virtual reality and video games

51
00:01:33,685 --> 00:01:35,368
and if you take even just a few minutes

52
00:01:35,367 --> 00:01:37,422
to peruse Stephenson's work, particularly his longer novels,

53
00:01:37,423 --> 00:01:39,024
like Cryptonomicon or Quicksilver,

54
00:01:39,024 --> 00:01:40,411
you start to realize that this is a guy

55
00:01:40,412 --> 00:01:42,358
with a ridiculously wide array of knowledge

56
00:01:42,358 --> 00:01:45,253
and he has this uncanny ability to blend complex topics

57
00:01:45,254 --> 00:01:48,048
like Sumerian mythology with really weird plot lines

58
00:01:48,049 --> 00:01:49,700
involving a katana-wielding swordsman,

59
00:01:49,700 --> 00:01:52,768
who delivers pizza for the Mafia and somehow it all works.

60
00:01:52,769 --> 00:01:54,930
Among science fiction readers like myself,

61
00:01:54,930 --> 00:01:55,958
few would disagree that Stephenson

62
00:01:55,959 --> 00:01:57,289
is one of the titans of the genre

63
00:01:57,289 --> 00:02:00,092
and even commands respect outside of literary circles,

64
00:02:00,093 --> 00:02:02,057
he shared the stage at Arizona State University

65
00:02:02,057 --> 00:02:04,238
with people like Neil DeGrass Tyson, Bill Nye,

66
00:02:04,237 --> 00:02:05,747
theoretical physicist, Brian Green

67
00:02:05,748 --> 00:02:07,409
and he's even worked as an advisor

68
00:02:07,411 --> 00:02:09,769
to Jeff Bezos's space company, Blue Origin,

69
00:02:09,769 --> 00:02:10,869
so you might find it surprising

70
00:02:10,868 --> 00:02:13,682
that Stephenson's first novel, a book called The Big U

71
00:02:13,682 --> 00:02:15,757
initially wasn't very successful at all,

72
00:02:15,758 --> 00:02:18,767
in fact Stephenson himself isn't very proud of it, stating,

73
00:02:18,768 --> 00:02:21,891
"The Big U is what it is, a first novel written in a hurry

74
00:02:21,890 --> 00:02:23,833
"by a young man a long time ago,"

75
00:02:23,834 --> 00:02:26,330
and for a long time after its publication in 1984,

76
00:02:26,330 --> 00:02:28,463
the book was almost impossible to find,

77
00:02:28,462 --> 00:02:30,123
it was only Stephenson's later success

78
00:02:30,123 --> 00:02:31,862
that convinced Harper Collins to republish it.

79
00:02:31,862 --> 00:02:33,384
Now if you look at the reviews of this book

80
00:02:33,385 --> 00:02:35,840
over on a site like GoodReads, you find that most people

81
00:02:35,842 --> 00:02:37,459
don't think that this is a bad book,

82
00:02:37,459 --> 00:02:39,165
it doesn't have a stellar score,

83
00:02:39,164 --> 00:02:41,744
but it's not terrible either and this kind of makes sense,

84
00:02:41,745 --> 00:02:44,076
you would expect to see in this earlier work

85
00:02:44,076 --> 00:02:45,946
some of the elephants that, some of the elephants,

86
00:02:45,947 --> 00:02:47,917
some of the elements that would later be refined

87
00:02:47,917 --> 00:02:49,757
into his more successful works,

88
00:02:49,757 --> 00:02:51,765
but the key point is that it's not something

89
00:02:51,764 --> 00:02:54,643
Stephenson was proud of and yet he published it anyway

90
00:02:54,644 --> 00:02:56,238
and then a second book, Zodiac,

91
00:02:56,237 --> 00:02:57,771
which also didn't really make waves,

92
00:02:57,771 --> 00:03:01,080
but with each published book, Stephenson honed his craft

93
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:02,886
and then finally he published Snow Crash,

94
00:03:02,887 --> 00:03:05,008
which was wildly successful and since then,

95
00:03:05,008 --> 00:03:07,990
he's continued to write bigger and more ambitious stories.

96
00:03:07,990 --> 00:03:10,312
Okay, so maybe Stephenson's example isn't enough for you,

97
00:03:10,312 --> 00:03:12,465
so let's look at one more case study for good measure

98
00:03:12,466 --> 00:03:13,299
and this time, I wanna look

99
00:03:13,299 --> 00:03:14,833
at the game developer, Matt Thorson,

100
00:03:14,832 --> 00:03:17,224
Thorson was one of the developers of Tower Fall Ascension,

101
00:03:17,225 --> 00:03:20,467
which is by far, hands down one of my all time

102
00:03:20,468 --> 00:03:23,556
favorite games, the simple, but ultra precise controls,

103
00:03:23,556 --> 00:03:26,584
the deceptively deep strategy and the ultra fast gameplay

104
00:03:26,585 --> 00:03:28,621
make it ridiculously fun to play with friends

105
00:03:28,622 --> 00:03:29,672
and it's even made its way

106
00:03:29,671 --> 00:03:31,540
to big fighting game tournaments like Evo.

107
00:03:31,540 --> 00:03:33,592
Tower Fall was a really successful game

108
00:03:33,592 --> 00:03:35,344
and Thorson's upcoming game, Celeste

109
00:03:35,346 --> 00:03:37,705
looks to be even more ambitious and polished

110
00:03:37,705 --> 00:03:40,035
and I cannot wait to play it in January,

111
00:03:40,036 --> 00:03:41,810
so Matt Thorson is obviously a really talented

112
00:03:41,810 --> 00:03:43,906
game developer, but the reason that I love him so much

113
00:03:43,906 --> 00:03:46,410
as an example here is because on his website,

114
00:03:46,411 --> 00:03:49,174
he has left a record of almost every game he's made,

115
00:03:49,175 --> 00:03:50,889
you can scroll through and see almost everything

116
00:03:50,889 --> 00:03:52,659
he's developed since 2004

117
00:03:52,659 --> 00:03:54,572
and you can even download most of the games

118
00:03:54,574 --> 00:03:55,719
and play them for yourself,

119
00:03:55,718 --> 00:03:58,352
which gives you a really visceral picture of his progression

120
00:03:58,354 --> 00:04:00,555
and these early games aren't bad at all,

121
00:04:00,556 --> 00:04:03,318
but there's a stark difference between these earlier efforts

122
00:04:03,318 --> 00:04:05,689
like Jumper and a game like Celeste,

123
00:04:05,689 --> 00:04:07,154
so Matt Thorson is another great example

124
00:04:07,155 --> 00:04:08,550
of the power of intermedia goals

125
00:04:08,550 --> 00:04:11,332
and the history on his website is a perfect illustration

126
00:04:11,331 --> 00:04:12,681
of the skilled development, that's brought about

127
00:04:12,681 --> 00:04:14,328
when you regularly finish things

128
00:04:14,330 --> 00:04:16,205
on a somewhat restricted timescale.

129
00:04:16,204 --> 00:04:18,239
Of course, if I'm gonna make an argument for the strategy

130
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:19,899
of detouring from the grand vision,

131
00:04:19,899 --> 00:04:22,398
of regular delivery on goals with smaller scope,

132
00:04:22,399 --> 00:04:23,784
then I do need to acknowledge the cases,

133
00:04:23,785 --> 00:04:25,464
where it doesn't seem to apply,

134
00:04:25,464 --> 00:04:27,766
so let's look at the case of Stardew Valley,

135
00:04:27,767 --> 00:04:29,453
this game is a brilliantly crafted homage

136
00:04:29,454 --> 00:04:32,376
to the classics of the farm RPG genre, like Harvest Moon

137
00:04:32,375 --> 00:04:35,052
and by all accounts, it has been wildly successful,

138
00:04:35,053 --> 00:04:37,948
at the moment it's got almost 70,000 reviews on Steam

139
00:04:37,949 --> 00:04:39,897
with overwhelmingly positive sentiment

140
00:04:39,896 --> 00:04:41,305
and last time I checked, it was near the top

141
00:04:41,307 --> 00:04:44,112
of the bestsellers list on the Switch game store as well

142
00:04:44,112 --> 00:04:47,110
and all this success is deserved, it's an excellent game,

143
00:04:47,110 --> 00:04:49,859
it's got deep and rewarding mechanics, there's a ton to do,

144
00:04:49,858 --> 00:04:51,691
the graphics are beautiful for the style

145
00:04:51,692 --> 00:04:53,645
and the music's pretty darn good as well

146
00:04:53,644 --> 00:04:56,753
and the crazy thing is the game's developer, Eric Barone

147
00:04:56,754 --> 00:04:58,659
did all of it, the coding, the art,

148
00:04:58,660 --> 00:05:00,067
the music, like literally everything,

149
00:05:00,067 --> 00:05:02,562
in total he spent over four years working on this game

150
00:05:02,562 --> 00:05:04,610
and honestly, it's a pretty astounding feat

151
00:05:04,612 --> 00:05:07,217
and as far as I can tell at least, it's his first game,

152
00:05:07,218 --> 00:05:08,172
before working on it,

153
00:05:08,172 --> 00:05:10,212
he did graduate with a Computer Science degree,

154
00:05:10,213 --> 00:05:12,124
but he was working as an usher at a movie theater,

155
00:05:12,125 --> 00:05:13,397
it's his first real effort,

156
00:05:13,396 --> 00:05:15,549
so at least as far as his public record is concerned,

157
00:05:15,550 --> 00:05:17,650
Eric Barone is proof that you can indeed

158
00:05:17,649 --> 00:05:20,100
achieve something great on your first try.

159
00:05:20,101 --> 00:05:22,130
Given that, let me put it to you this way,

160
00:05:22,132 --> 00:05:23,701
if you know that you're that lone genius type,

161
00:05:23,701 --> 00:05:25,935
if you've been toiling away quietly on your masterpiece

162
00:05:25,935 --> 00:05:28,157
in between classes and underappreciated shifts

163
00:05:28,158 --> 00:05:30,807
as an Applebee's line cook, then feel free to ignore me,

164
00:05:30,807 --> 00:05:32,615
the reasoned arguments of somebody on the internet

165
00:05:32,617 --> 00:05:34,911
could never outshine your conviction anyway

166
00:05:34,911 --> 00:05:36,840
and honestly, you're probably not even watching this,

167
00:05:36,839 --> 00:05:38,657
but if you really do think that you're that lone genius,

168
00:05:38,658 --> 00:05:39,742
who shouldn't detour away

169
00:05:39,742 --> 00:05:41,474
from the grand vision for anything,

170
00:05:41,475 --> 00:05:43,578
then you had better be able to honestly say

171
00:05:43,577 --> 00:05:46,431
that you're putting in the work on a regular basis

172
00:05:46,432 --> 00:05:48,133
and Eric Barone is a great example of this,

173
00:05:48,132 --> 00:05:50,430
he often worked 10 hours a day or more,

174
00:05:50,430 --> 00:05:51,803
while working on Stardew Valley,

175
00:05:51,803 --> 00:05:53,135
if on the other hand,

176
00:05:53,136 --> 00:05:54,918
the grand scope of your ambitious project

177
00:05:54,918 --> 00:05:56,202
is more daunting than anything,

178
00:05:56,201 --> 00:05:58,479
if you find yourself working in fits and starts,

179
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:00,528
often abandoning the project for months at a time,

180
00:06:00,529 --> 00:06:02,329
if you find yourself coming home from class or work

181
00:06:02,331 --> 00:06:04,002
and deciding that you deserve to take a break

182
00:06:04,002 --> 00:06:05,068
and just play some Overwatch,

183
00:06:05,069 --> 00:06:06,962
rather than working for four more hours,

184
00:06:06,963 --> 00:06:08,808
then you're just like me and most other people,

185
00:06:08,807 --> 00:06:11,291
you just don't have that nearly rabid level of focus

186
00:06:11,293 --> 00:06:14,486
and determination required to work for years in obscurity,

187
00:06:14,487 --> 00:06:16,130
without any feedback or recognition

188
00:06:16,129 --> 00:06:18,694
or even the satisfaction of finishing a project

189
00:06:18,696 --> 00:06:20,486
and honestly, that's fine,

190
00:06:20,485 --> 00:06:22,791
there's a reason we don't lock six-year olds in a closet

191
00:06:22,793 --> 00:06:24,279
and tell them to learn calculus,

192
00:06:24,278 --> 00:06:25,822
most of us do better, when given a task,

193
00:06:25,824 --> 00:06:27,912
that stretches our capabilities to a point,

194
00:06:27,911 --> 00:06:31,181
but isn't so far beyond them, that it seems impossible

195
00:06:31,182 --> 00:06:32,476
and getting regular feedback

196
00:06:32,476 --> 00:06:33,865
or being able to see a progression

197
00:06:33,865 --> 00:06:36,751
of finished projects is a very good thing,

198
00:06:36,752 --> 00:06:37,820
so here is the one idea,

199
00:06:37,821 --> 00:06:39,605
that I want you to chew on for this week

200
00:06:39,605 --> 00:06:40,780
and keep in the back of your head

201
00:06:40,781 --> 00:06:42,356
the next time you're setting a goal,

202
00:06:42,355 --> 00:06:44,774
restrict your timescale, ask yourself what you could

203
00:06:44,776 --> 00:06:46,316
get done in a week or even a day,

204
00:06:46,317 --> 00:06:47,512
if you wanna make video games,

205
00:06:47,512 --> 00:06:49,971
challenge yourself to make one game this week,

206
00:06:49,973 --> 00:06:52,320
even if it's just a red block, that jumps

207
00:06:52,319 --> 00:06:53,712
or if maybe you wanna learn how to cook,

208
00:06:53,713 --> 00:06:56,147
find a meal, that uses just a few simple ingredients

209
00:06:56,146 --> 00:06:58,129
and make it tonight and then next week,

210
00:06:58,129 --> 00:07:00,082
make something a little bit more ambitious

211
00:07:00,083 --> 00:07:00,926
and build from there.

212
00:07:00,925 --> 00:07:02,627
It's often the case that your grand vision

213
00:07:02,627 --> 00:07:04,191
is full of challenges and difficulties,

214
00:07:04,192 --> 00:07:06,026
that you aren't even aware of yet,

215
00:07:06,026 --> 00:07:08,300
this is called second-order incompetence,

216
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:11,010
you literally don't know what you don't know,

217
00:07:11,012 --> 00:07:12,720
but by taking on a series of smaller projects,

218
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:14,708
each of which stretch your capabilities

219
00:07:14,708 --> 00:07:16,990
to just a little bit beyond where they are right now,

220
00:07:16,990 --> 00:07:18,627
you start building that base of knowledge,

221
00:07:18,627 --> 00:07:20,292
that's going to allow you

222
00:07:20,293 --> 00:07:23,346
to someday execute on that grand vision.

223
00:07:23,346 --> 00:07:24,587
Of course, if the goal you're setting for yourself

224
00:07:24,588 --> 00:07:26,553
is something that you don't quite know how to do yet,

225
00:07:26,552 --> 00:07:27,963
like cooking or game development,

226
00:07:27,963 --> 00:07:30,028
then it can also be very useful to seek out experts,

227
00:07:30,029 --> 00:07:31,664
who have been there and who can teach you

228
00:07:31,665 --> 00:07:32,517
the most efficient techniques

229
00:07:32,517 --> 00:07:34,216
and one of the best places on the internet

230
00:07:34,216 --> 00:07:36,409
to find those experts is Skillshare,

231
00:07:36,410 --> 00:07:37,889
Skillshare is an online learning platform

232
00:07:37,889 --> 00:07:40,567
with over 17,000 courses in subjects ranging

233
00:07:40,567 --> 00:07:42,993
from Presentation Skills to Graphic Design

234
00:07:42,994 --> 00:07:44,008
to Javascript Programming

235
00:07:44,009 --> 00:07:46,068
and in addition to those more professional topics,

236
00:07:46,067 --> 00:07:49,005
Skillshare also has over 400 courses in cooking,

237
00:07:49,005 --> 00:07:50,549
which is what I wanna highlight this week,

238
00:07:50,550 --> 00:07:52,646
because one of the things I'm working on right now

239
00:07:52,646 --> 00:07:53,678
is becoming a better cook

240
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:55,664
and this has been really rewarding,

241
00:07:55,663 --> 00:07:56,625
I found that learning how to cook

242
00:07:56,625 --> 00:07:58,076
results in me eating healthier,

243
00:07:58,077 --> 00:07:59,619
makes me spend less money on food,

244
00:07:59,620 --> 00:08:01,319
because I'm not going out as often,

245
00:08:01,319 --> 00:08:03,085
but also most surprisingly,

246
00:08:03,086 --> 00:08:05,473
it's made the process of cooking more enjoyable.

247
00:08:05,473 --> 00:08:07,497
In the past, I've always seen cooking as a chore,

248
00:08:07,497 --> 00:08:09,952
something that I wanted to get done as quickly as possible,

249
00:08:09,951 --> 00:08:12,691
so I could go and do other things or do more work,

250
00:08:12,692 --> 00:08:14,725
but I found that learning new techniques

251
00:08:14,725 --> 00:08:16,797
and challenging myself to make new recipes

252
00:08:16,798 --> 00:08:18,762
actually makes the process really enjoyable,

253
00:08:18,762 --> 00:08:20,967
even kind of meditative and when I get into it,

254
00:08:20,968 --> 00:08:23,166
I don't care how long it takes, because I'm having fun,

255
00:08:23,166 --> 00:08:24,736
so for those reasons, I think that cooking

256
00:08:24,737 --> 00:08:26,400
is one of those skills that basically everyone

257
00:08:26,401 --> 00:08:27,709
could benefit from learning

258
00:08:27,709 --> 00:08:29,454
and on Skillshare, Kenny Monroe's course,

259
00:08:29,454 --> 00:08:31,210
Think Like a Chef is a great introduction,

